AIMS
This s tudy investigated the effect of a ﬁxed dose combination of
lopinavir/ritonavir on the pharmacokinetics (PK) of selexipag and its
active metabolite ACT-333679.
METHODS
This was an open label, randomized, sin gle centre, t wo way, crossover
study. Twenty healthy male subjects were treated with a single dose of
400 μg se lexipag alone and in combination with multipl e doses of
lopinavir/ritonavir (400/100 mg) twice daily.
RESULTS
The results showed that lopinavir/ritonavir approximately doubled the
exposure to selexipag. The area under the plasma concentration–time
curve from time zero to inﬁnity (AUC(0,1) and the maximum plasma
concentration (C
max
) of selexipag were 2.2- and 2.1-fold h igher, re-
spectively, than under selexipag alone, with a 90% conﬁdence interval
(CI)ofthegeometricmeanratio(GMR)of1.9,2.7and1.7,2.6,respec-
tively. For ACT-333679, the clinically more relevant component of
selexipag, systemic exposure was increased by 8% (GMR of AUC(0,1)
1.1, 90% CI 0.9, 1.3), when lopinavir/ritonavir was co-administered with
selexipag.
The most frequently reported adverse event (AE) was headache. A
single dose of selexipag, administered either alone or together with
multiple doses of lopinavir/ritonavir, was safe and well tolerated.
CONCLUSIONS
Lopinavir/ritonavir does not affect the PK parameters o f selexipag and
ACT-333679 to a clinically relevant extent. Therefore, adaptation of the
selexipag dose is not required when co-administered with inhibitors of
the organic anion-transporting polypeptide (OATP) 1B1/ 1B3,
P-glycoprotein (P-gp) and/or CY P3A4.

Introduction
Pulmonary arterial hypertension (PAH) is a life-threatening
complication in patients with human immunodeﬁciency vi-
rus (HIV) infection and is observed in approximately 0.5% of
these patients [1–6]. In patients with PAH, prostacyclin con-
centrations in the lung are markedly decreased [7, 8]. Pros-
tacyclin, mainly released by vascular endothelial cells, is a
potent vasodilator, inhibitor of platelet aggregation, and
moderator of vascular smooth muscle cell proliferation,
migration and differentiation [9]. Thus, prostacyclin contrib-
utes to the maintenance of vascular homeostasis and its
decrease leads to vasoconstriction and proliferation of
vascular smooth muscle cells. Therefore, restoration of
prostacyclin receptor (IP receptor) signalling is an effective
strategy in the treatment of PAH [10]. Improvements with
intravenous (i.v.) prostacyclin (epoprostenol) infusions have
been reported in patients who have PAH [11–13] and PAH
associated with HIV infection [14, 15]. However, due to its
short half-life and chemical instability, long-term i.v.
epoprostenol therapy requires a permanently implanted
central venous catheter and a portable infusion pump,
exposing patients to a series of complications including
catheter-related embolism or thrombosis, infection and
delivery system malfunctions, resulting in poorly tolerated,
rapid overdosing or underdosing [16–18].
Selexipag (2-{4-[(5,6-diphenylpyrazin-2-yl)(isopropyl)amino]
butoxy}-N-(methylsulfonyl)acetamide (ACT-293987, NS-304)) is
a new, orally active, selective IP receptor agonist which tar-
gets the prostacyclin pathway and is structurally and phar-
macologically distinct from prostanoids [19]. It is currently
under development for the treatment of PAH [20–23]. In a
phase IIa proof-of-concept study in patients with PAH,
treatment with selexipag resulted in a statistically signiﬁ-
cant 30% reduction in pulmonary vascular resistance after
17 weeks, which was supported by an increase in cardiac
index and a decrease in systemic vascular resistance with-
out systemic hypotension [22].
The metabolism of selexipag is driven by initial hydrolysis
to its active me tabolite [19, 21], ACT-333679 (Figure 1), cata-
lyzed by a subclass of carboxylesterases 1 located in the liver.
It has also been shown that CYP2C8 and CYP3A4 are
involved in the metabolism of selexipag and ACT-333679,
whereas UDP-glucuronosyltransferase (UGT) enzymes,
UGT1A3 and UGT2B7, are also involved in the metabolism
of ACT-333679 (Actelion Pharmaceuticals Ltd, data on ﬁle).
Both selexipag and ACT-333679 are potent and selective
agonists of the human IP receptor [19, 23]. ACT-333679
is 15-fold more potent than selexipag [19, 23].
In vitro, selexipag and ACT-333679 have been identi-
ﬁed as weak substrates of OATP1B1 and OATP1B3, while
selexipag, but not the active metabolite, is a weak sub-
strate of the efﬂux pump P-gp (Actelion Pharmaceuticals
Ltd, data on ﬁle).
As biliary eli minatio n accounts for approximately 90%
of the excretion of selexipag and its metabolites in
animals and humans [24], subjects administered selexipag
concomitantly with inhibitors of CYP3A4, OATP and/or
P-gp may have an increased exposure to selexipag and/or
ACT-333679. Lopinavir/ritonavir is a ﬁxed dose protease
inhibitor combination used for the treatment of HIV infec-
tion that could be co-administered with selexipag in
patients who have PAH associated with HIV infection.
Lopinavir and ritonavir are known inhibitors of OATP1B1
and OATP1B3, but also of CYP3A4 and P-gp [25, 26], and
therefore this ﬁxed combination serves as a model inhibitor
to gain broader insight into the drug–drug interaction
propensity of selexipag and its main metabolite.
The purpose of this study was to investigate the effect of
the ﬁxed dose combination of lopinavir/ritonavir on the PK
of selexipag and its active metabolite ACT-333679 and to
evaluate the tolerability of single dose selexipag when ad-
ministered alone or in combination with lopinavir/ritonavir.
Lopinavir/ritonavir as the perpetrator drug was adminis-
tered in a multiple dose regimen at the highest recom-
mended dose. Selexipag as the victim drug was given as a
single dose in the dose-proportional range of PK. The study
was performed in healthy subjects, as ﬁndings in healthy
subjects can predict ﬁndings in the patient population for
which the drug is intended. Such studies usually provide
clearer data than patient studies because of a more homo-
geneous and standardized population, which is healthy and
not treated with concomitant medications.
Methods
Subjects
The Research Ethics Committee (Ethikkommission II,
Bismarckallee 8–12, 23795 Bad Segeberg, Germany)
reviewed and approved the study protocol and any
material provided to the study participants. This study
was conducted in full compliance with the principles of
the Declaration of Helsinki.
Twenty healthy male subjects were recruited in this
study and all provided written informed consent. For
determination o f the sample size, calculations were
carried out to assess the difference that can be detected
between selexipag with lopinavir/ri tonavir and selexipag
alone. The study set-up allowed for detection of a differ-
ence in AUC(0, 1) of at least 1.23-fold for selexipag and
1.14 for its metabolite.
Subjects were assessed to be healthy on the basis of
screening examinations. Signiﬁcant loss of blood
(≥250 ml) within 3 months prior to the start of trial, previ-
ous history of fainting, syncope, orthostatic hypotensi on,
vasovagal reactions, serum aspartate aminotransferase
and/or alanine aminotransferase >1.5 times the upper
limit of normal (ULN) at screening or history or clinica l
evidence of any condition that might affect the PK of
the study drugs were among the exclusion criteria.
Smoking within the last 3 months prior to screening

and use of any drug (including over-the-counter and
herbal medications), within 2 weeks prior to screening
and during t he study, were forbidden. In addition, during
the study conduct, subjects were not permitted to con-
sume any beverage or food that might affect the PK of
selexipag o r lopinavir/ritonavir.
Study design
This was a prospective, single centre, open label, ran-
domized, two treatment, two period, crossover, phase 1
study. T he participants were randomly assigned to one
of two treatment sequences: A/B or B/A. Treatment A
was a single dose of 400 μg selexipag administered in a
fasted state in the morning of day 1, f ollowed by an
observation period of 72 h. Treatment B was a ﬁxed
combination of lopinavir/ritonavir (400/100 mg) twice
dailyfor12daysplusasingledoseof400μg selexipag
administered concomitantly with the morning dose of
lopinavir/ritonavir on day 10 in the fasted state. Subjects
entered the clinic 1 day before the ﬁrst dosing and were
discharged 72 h after selexipag administration, i.e. in the
morning of day 4 (treatment A) or day 13 (treatment B)
after compl etion of the scheduled assessments a nd if
their m edical condition permitted. There was an ambula-
tory wash-out period of 14 to 22 days between the two
treatment periods. The end-of-study (EOS) visit was
performed 7 ± 2 days after the last blood sample for PK.
Safety and tolerability were a ssessed throughout the
study. Records of all adverse events (AEs), vital signs,
electrocardiogram (ECG) variables and laboratory param-
eters were collected during the two treatment periods
and the wash-o ut period. All subjects were followed up
for AEs that were ongoing at EOS by telephone, 30–32
days after the last stud y drug administratio n.
Blood sampling
Blood samples (4 ml) for determination of selexipag and
ACT-333679 concentrations were collected into heparin
tubes on day 1 (treatment A) and day 10 (treatment B)
before morning administration and regularly until 72 h
after study drug intake.
Bioanalytical analysis
Selexipag and ACT-333679 were quantiﬁed in plasma
using a validated liqu id ch romatography with tandem
mass spectrometry (LC-MS/MS) method as described
previously [27]. As part of the sampling process,
plasma was acidiﬁed with 1
M hydrochloric acid to avoid
hydrolysis of the acylglucuronide of ACT-333679 back to
ACT-333679.
The method was linear in t he concentration range
0.01 to 20.0 ng ml
–1
and 0.05 to 20.0 ng ml
–1
for selexipag
and ACT-333679, respectively. The lower limit of quantiﬁ-
cation (LOQ) was 0.01 ng ml
–1
for both selexipag and
ACT-333679. Concentrations were c alculated by interpo-
lation fro m calibration curves. Precision (% CV) of the as -
say w as ≤9.8% for selexipag and ≤10.8% for ACT-333679,
whereas the inter-assay accuracy was ≤3.8% and ≤4.7%,
respectively.
Pharmacokinetic analysis
PK parameters were evaluated using Phoenix WinNonlin
software, version 6.1 (Pharsight Corporation, Cary, NC, USA).
The PK parameters for selexipag and ACT-333679 were
derived by non-compartmental analysis of the plasma
concentration–time proﬁles. AUC(0,1) was calculated by
combining the area under the plasma concentration–time
curve from time 0 to the last measured concentration above
the LOQ (AUC(0,t)) and AUC
extra

inﬁnity. AUC(0,t) was calculated according to the linear trap-
ezoidal rule using the measured concentration–time values
above the LOQ. C
max
andtimetoreachthemaximum

max
) were determined directly from
the measured individual plasma concentrations of selexipag
and its active metabolite. The half-life (t
½

Geometric means of the PK parameters of selexipag and
ACT-333679 and their 95% CIs were generated and com-
pared in the presence and absence of lopinavir/ritonavir.
Statistical analysis
Statistical analyses were car ried out using SAS® software,
version 9.3 (SAS Institute, Cary, NC, USA). The effect of the
ﬁxed combination of lopinavir/ritonavir on AUC(0,1),
C

using the ratio of geometric means of test (treatment B)
vs. reference (treatment A) and its 90% CI by means of
linear mixed effects models. In these models, treatment,
period and treatment sequence were ﬁxed effects and
subject-nested within treatment sequence was the
random effect.

Results
A total of 20 healthy male subjects (23–53 years old) were
enrolled and received study drugs as planned. Of them,
18 were Caucasian and two were Asian. All completed
the study according to the protocol and none was
excluded from the analysis.

Discussion
This study aimed at investigating the effect of lopinavir/
ritonavir on the PK of selexipag and ACT-333679. Selexipag
is a ﬁrst-in-class non-prostanoid IP receptor agonist, under
development for the treatment of PAH. The results of this
drug–drug interaction study, together with further data
from the pivotal phase III study, will support a clinical
decision on the necessity of dose adjustments, when PAH
patients are concomitantly treated with selexipag and
inhibitors of OATP1B1/ OATP1B3, P-gp and/or CYP3A4.
The results of this study show that co-administration
of lopinavir/rito navir and selexipag increased the expo-
sure to selexipag approximately two-fold . However, to
assess the potential clinical impact of this PK interaction,
the P K of ACT-333679, the main active metabolite of
selexipag has to be considered. Since ACT-333679 is a
15-fold more po tent selective agonist at human IP recep-
tors than selexipag [19, 23] and its exposure is three to
four times higher, the metabolite is considered to pres-
ent the relevant component in selexipag therapy. For
ACT-333679, the GMR of AUC(0,1) and its 90% CI
indicated that the total exposure was comparable after
administration of selexipag alone and in combinatio n
with lo pinavir/rito navir and the increases of 8% and
33% observed for A UC(0,1)andC
max
, respectively, were
not considered to be clinically relevant.
The effect of lopinavir/ritonavir on the PK of selexipag
with a two-fold increase in exposure could theoretically
be explained by the inhibitory effect of lopinavir/ritonavir
on OATP transporters and P-gp, but also by inhibition of
CYP3A4 (Actelion Pharmaceuticals Ltd, data on ﬁle) in the
liver and in the gastrointestinal tract. Increased selexipag
C
max
and AUC(0,1) of selexipag could indicate enhanced
bioavailability due to pre-systemic effects of lopinavir/
ritonavir in the gastrointestinal tract. Oral bioavailability of
selexipag in monkeys is known to be low. However this

has not yet been assessed in man. In spite of this possible
transporter-mediated drug–drug interaction and CYP
inhibition, no relevant effect of lopinavir/ritonavir on the
exposure to ACT-333679 has been shown in this study.
Other mechanisms, such as passive diffusion, contribute
to the entry of both entities, selexipag and ACT-333679,
into cells, reducing the dependency on transporters.
In addition to CYP3A4 and CYP2C8, UGT1A3 and
UGT2B7 have been shown to be involved in the m etabo-
lism of ACT-333679 (Actelion Pharmaceuticals Ltd, data
on ﬁle). The metabolic pathways of ACT-333679 are only
partially CYP3A4 dependent. Moreover, the inhibitory
effect of lopinavi r/ritonavir on CYP3A4 may be pa rtly
compensated by simultaneous induction of the metabo-
lism of ACT-333679 through UGTs. Aside from its strong
inhibitory activity on CYP3A4, lopinavir/ritonav ir has
been shown to increase the biotransformation of some
drugs by inducing glucuronidation, catalyzed by UGT,
although the clinical relevance of thi s effect is not clear
[25, 28–30]. This is further corroborated by the change
in t
½
of ACT-333679, which shows a 35% decrease when
lopinavir/ritonavir is administered with selexipag, reﬂecting
an increase in metabolism of ACT-333679, that might be
due to UGT induction.
Regarding safety, no relevant difference in AE inci-
dence was observed when comparing t he combination
treatment (selexipag + lo pinavir/ritonavir) vs. selexipag
alone. Selexipag alone was well tolerated and the
incidence and nature of the AEs of the present study
are consistent with previous studies [24, 27, 31]. Overall,
under the conditions of this study, the combination
treatment was also well tolerated in health y subjects.
In conclusion, although the present study has shown
that concomitant administration of lopinavir/ritonavir and
selexipag approximately doubled the exposure to
selexipag, the overall exposure to ACT-333679, the most
clinically relevant component of selexipag, was increased
by only 1.08-fold. Thus, the results of this study suggest that
the extent of change in PK parameters of selexipag and its
main active metabolite ACT-333679, when lopinavir/
ritonavir is given concomitantly with selexipag as compared
with selexipag alone, is not anticipated to result in a
clinically meaningfu l interaction. Therefore, adaptation
of the dose of selexipag might no t be required w hen ad-
ministered concomitantly with inhibitors of transporters
OATP1B1/OATP1B3 (e.g. ataza navir, ciclosporin), P-gp
(e.g. verapamil, ketoconazole, tacrolimus) or CYP3A4
(e.g. saquinavir, ketoconazole, clarithromycin).
